data.chText: 使惊吓；使吓一跳；使大吃一惊
data.enText: to surprise sb suddenly in a way that slightly shocks or frightens them

data.chText: 我不是存心要吓唬你。
data.enText: I didn't mean to startle you.

data.chText: 爆炸声使马受了惊。
data.enText: The explosion startled the horse.

data.chText: 她的问题让我大吃一惊。
data.enText: I was startled by her question.

data.chText: 我一进办公室，发现她坐在里面，把我吓了一跳。

data.hoverText: 动词+名词短语+带to的不定式

data.enText: It startled me to find her sitting in my office.

data.chText: 她用吃惊的目光看着他。
data.enText: She looked at him with startled eyes.

data.chText: 他显得很惊讶。
data.enText: He looked startled.

data.chText: 她像受惊的兔子似的跳了回去。
data.enText: She jumped back like a startled rabbit.

data.chText: 以上各词均含使害怕、使恐惧之义。
data.enText: All these words mean to make sb afraid.
frighten

data.chText: 指（常为突如其来地）使惊吓、使惊恐：
data.enText: to make sb feel afraid, often suddenly

data.chText: 他掏出一把枪，把他们吓跑了。
data.enText: He brought out a gun and frightened them off.
scare

data.chText: 指使害怕、使恐惧：
data.enText: to make sb feel afraid

data.chText: 他们设法把那些熊吓跑了。
data.enText: They managed to scare the bears away.

data.chText: 用frighten还是scare？
以上两词均为通用词，意思非常相似，用任何一个均可。scare较frighten稍非正式。
data.enText: Both are very common words, and are very similar, so you can use either one correctly. Scare is slightly more informal than frighten .
frighten or scare?
alarm

data.chText: 指使惊恐、使害怕、使担心：
data.enText: to make sb anxious or afraid

data.chText: 谁都不认真对待这个问题，我非常担心。
data.enText: It alarms me that nobody takes this problem seriously.

data.chText: 用frighten还是alarm？
alarm的主语通常为事物、事件或形势，而非人：
data.enText: The subject of alarm is usually a thing, an event or a situation rather than a person.
You're alarming me.

data.chText: alarm用于形容不好的事情或危险将要发生的心情，多为忧虑而非真的害怕。
data.enText: It is used to describe a feeling that sth unpleasant or dangerous is going to happen in the future, and the feeling is often more of worry than actual fear.
frighten or alarm?
intimidate

data.chText: 指恐吓、威胁：
data.enText: to frighten or threaten sb so that they feel nervous or so that they will do what you want

data.chText: 他们被控胁迫选民投他们的票。
data.enText: They were accused of intimidating people into voting for them.
startle

data.chText: 指使惊吓、使吓一跳、使大吃一惊：
data.enText: to make sb feel suddenly frightened or surprised, usually because of sth sudden or unexpected

data.chText: 突然发出的响声吓了她一跳。
data.enText: A sudden noise startled her.
Stop it! You're frightening/scaring me !
Oh sorry. I didn't mean to frighten/scare/startle you .
to frighten/scare sb/sth away/off
I was frightened/scared/alarmed/intimidated/startled by what he said.
He frightened/scared/intimidated me into telling him what happened.

data.text: surprise ♦ startle ♦ amaze ♦ stun ♦ astonish ♦ take sb aback ♦ astound

data.chText: 以上各词均含使惊奇、使诧异之义。
data.enText: These words all mean to make sb feel surprised.
surprise

data.chText: 指使惊奇、使诧异、使感到意外：
data.enText: to give sb the feeling that you get when sth happens that you do not expect or do not understand, or sth that you do expect does not happen; to make sb feel surprised

data.chText: 这一结果完全在我的意料之中。
data.enText: The outcome didn't surprise me at all.
startle

data.chText: 指惊吓、使吓一跳、使大吃一惊：
data.enText: to surprise sb suddenly in a way that slightly shocks or frightens them

data.chText: 对不起，我不是存心要吓唬你。
data.enText: Sorry, I didn't mean to startle you.

data.chText: 爆炸声使马受了惊。
data.enText: The explosion startled the horse.
amaze

data.chText: 指使惊奇、使惊愕、使惊诧：
data.enText: to surprise sb very much

data.chText: 仅仅地方之大就使她十分惊奇。
data.enText: Just the huge size of the place amazed her.
stun

data.chText: （常用于报章）指使震惊、使惊愕、使目瞪口呆
data.enText: ( rather informal ) (often in newspapers) to surprise or shock sb so much that they cannot think clearly or speak
astonish

data.chText: 指使十分惊讶、使大为惊奇：
data.enText: to surprise sb very much

data.chText: 这消息使大家十分惊讶。
data.enText: The news astonished everyone.

data.chText: 用amaze还是astonish？
上述两词意思相同，多数情况下使用任何一个均可。astonish总的说来比amaze的使用频率稍低。但如果指某事既使人惊愕又使人羞愧则较常用astonish：
data.enText: These two words have the same meaning and in most cases you can use either. Astonish is in general slightly less frequent than amaze , but if you are talking about sth that both surprises you and makes you feel ashamed, it is more usual to use astonish .

data.chText: 他对自己的愚蠢感到十分震惊。
data.enText: He was astonished by his own stupidity.
amaze or astonish?
take sb aback

data.chText: （尤指不好的事）使大吃一惊、使震惊：
data.enText: [usually passive] (especially of sth negative) to surprise or shock sb

data.chText: 她敌视的反应使我们大吃一惊。
data.enText: We were rather taken aback by her hostile reaction.
astound

data.chText: 指使震惊、使大惊：
data.enText: to surprise or shock sb very much

data.chText: 他的傲慢使她震惊。
data.enText: His arrogance astounded her.
It surprises sb/startles sb/amazes sb/stuns sb/astonishes sb/takes sb aback/astounds sb
to surprise/startle/amaze/stun/astonish/astound sb that…
to surprise/amaze sb what/how…
to surprise/startle/amaze/stun/astonish/astound sb to know/find/learn/see/hear…
to be surprised/startled/stunned into (doing) sth
to absolutely amaze sb/stun sb/astonish sb/astound sb
sth never ceases to surprise/amaze/astonish/astound sb

tr: move or jump suddenly, as if in surprise or alarm
example: She startled when I walked into the room

value.def: If something sudden and unexpected startles you, it surprises and frightens you slightly.

example.ex: Sorry, I didn't mean to startle you...
example.tran: 对不起，我不是故意想吓你一跳的。

example.ex: The news will startle the City.
example.tran: 这个消息会让伦敦商业区的人们大吃一惊。

example.ex: Martha gave her a startled look.
example.tran: 玛莎吃惊地看了她一眼。
